textBeforeTable: Students need to consider many aspects of a school when making a decision about their education. The following table offers a comparison of these three schools. Comparison of Schools The automotive repair technician associate's degree program consists of 117 credits and features courses in engine performance, shop practices, engine repair and brake systems. The program can be completed in six terms and can lead to positions at repair shops, dealership service centers and specialty shops. Automotive Repair Technician Associate of Applied Science The 89-credit automotive repair technician program at Lake Washington Institute of Technology can prepare students for immediate employment upon graduation. In addition to basic core requirements, students also complete higher-level courses in engine performance, heating and air conditioning service, manual transmissions and brake systems. Students have the option to gain work experience while earning credit during the final two terms of the program, subject to approval from their instructors. Automotive Repair Technician Certificate of Proficiency The general service technician certificate is a 32-credit program that provides basic training in the field. Courses in this introductory program cover computer basics, business practices, electrical systems, mechanical principles and maintenance procedures. Students who complete this program are eligible to transfer their credits to the automotive repair technician certificate or associate's degree program. This program can prepare students to take two of the ASE certification exams.
